Birth weights and Smoking

Next, I collapsed all misc. white races into one singular set. This was suggested in the problem descriptions and allows me to better analyze the data in question 2 as stated above.

Also after looking at the plots for ‘parity,’ I decided to group all pregnancies/births greater than or equal to 6 as one set, with all others remaining to their own grouping.

Looking through these initial plots, no major malformations or abnormalities present themselves. The data looks relatively linear as it is so I am not inclined to do any transformations of the data.

#regression model
birthModel <- lm(bwt.oz ~ as.factor(smoke) * as.factor(mrace) + mht + mpregwt + as.factor(med) * inc + mage * as.factor(parity), data = smoking)

After no apparent abnormalities or errors came up from looking at the plots, I decided not to use any transformations as I do not believe they well help. After minimalizing the different white races into one, I looked at the other variables to see if they needed to be factorized. I made all non-continious variables (smoke, mrace, med, and parity) factors for the model. This allows a much more straight interpreation from the model for prediction purposes.

With the model I decided to use interaction between education and income, as they had a strong correlation between to two variables. We’ve seen in other data sets that more education tends to lead to better income.

Next I decided to do an interaction between age and parity. The reasoning behind this is, logicallically thinking, child birth is a process that takes 40 weeks, therefore a woman who has multiple children will have to age approximately a year at bare minimum to do so.

raceBirthModel <- lm(bwt.oz ~ as.factor(smoke) + as.factor(mrace) + mht + mpregwt +
                       as.factor(med) * inc + mage * as.factor(parity), data = smoking)

Finally I took the question to mean that there may be an interaction between race and smoking. After comparing a model with an interaction and one with out I determined that the models were different enough to look at an interaction as the anova between the values returned a Pr(>F) of 0.1691.

Looking through the residual plots of all of the valuables, we can see that the model we used is accurate as the points on the plots are evenly distributed on both sides of the (0,0) line.

On to the questions: 1) Do mothers who smoke tend to give birth to babies with lower weights than mothers who do not smoke? What is a likely range for the difference in birth weights for smokers and non-smokers?

Yes, mother who smokes during pregnancy can expect to have a child between 11.57 to 6.91 ounces less than a pregnancy than doesn’t when all other factors are equal. This factor has the lowest P value at 2.15 x 10-14 compared to other factors. From this we can assume that the data is accurate within the model

2) Is there any evidence that the association between smoking and birth weight differs by mother’s race? If so, characterize those differences.

Yes, however there are some caveats. When looking at race seperately we can see that women who are identified as ‘Black,’ ‘Asian,’ or ‘Mixed’ will have a lower value for thier child’s birth weight between them and the baseline of a ‘White’ mother. The only race that has a range greater than the baseline is ‘Mexican’. When we create a model with an interaction between the variables ‘smoking’ and ‘mrace’ we notice that smoking and race trend changes that ‘Black’ mother’s children do not have the negative trend that they do compared to the baseline. ‘Asian’ and ‘Mixed,’ still have a negative correlation in comparison to child’s weight, however it is substantially more pernounced than without.

The P values for these interactions are all relatively high, ranging from 0.063 to 0.401, leading me to believe the interaction is present, but not how strong may remain in question

3) Are there other interesting associations with birth weight that are worth mentioning? So, the question is asking about the remaining predictor variables in the model and their associations with birth weight.

Yes, it should be worth mentioning that outside of smoking and race, parity has a strong correlation to birth weight, meaning, as a mother has more children the children will be larger/heavier after each successive birth. This holds true until about 6 or more children where the number of observation is limited, so it begins to break down the trend.
